                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. No. 811.712/65</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Order No. 212 of the Postmaster General</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_BAS1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Burleson</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d468fn1">From the <hi rend="italic">Daily
                            Bulletin of Orders Affecting the Postal Service</hi>, Apr. 7,
                        1917.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 6, 1917</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In consequence of the state of war now existing, the suspension of the exchange
                    of postal money orders between the United States and the German Empire is hereby
                    directed.</p>
                <p>Postmasters at all international money-order offices will govern themselves
                    accordingly. On and after this date they should refuse to issue orders on post
                    offices in the German Empire or any of its colonies or dependencies. They should
                    also decline to pay orders drawn upon them by German offices on or after the 6th
                    day of April.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BAS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">A. S. Burleson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
